Hi Amy:

Last week I sent an email with a proposal for an article on
heuristic search of a state-space. After I sent it I realized 
that I really did not explain why I thought the article would be
of interest to CUJ readers. Basically, this last year I have 
been learning about artificial inteligence so that I can create
an expert system for work. What I found was that most of the 
problems in AI really boil down to efficiently traversing a 
directed graph. This is true for games, theorem proving, the
computing language Prolog, and diagnostic programs (what I 
am working on), for example. What all this means is that a 
programmer must have a good understanding of search techniques 
to solve AI problems. The article I proposed is on the "best-first"
heuristic search algorithm for traversing a problem state-space.
This method is used to solve many of the "classic" AI problems,
N-queens, missionary and cannibals, and the 8-square. In many 
AI books (Nils Nilsson's Principles of AI, for example), the first
topic covered is heuristic search, best-first search.

Sorry about sending this with the first email. Thank you for your
interest.

Mike Rumore
mrumore@lucent.com



